< examples >

external_rec
   - A rectangular cloud is illuminated by external radiation.
     The radiation field is assumed to be isotropic.
     In other words, the cloud is embedded within an isotropic radiation field.

external_sph
   - A spherical cloud is illuminated by external radiation.
     The radiation field is assumed to be isotropic.

external_cyl
   - A cylinderical cloud is illuminated by external radiation.
     The cylinder is assumed to be symmetric about the z-axis.
     The radiation field is assumed to be isotropic.

point_source
   - A point radiation source is located at the center of a spherical (or rectangular) cloud.
     Radiation is isotropically emitted from the central source.

uniform_source
   - Radiation is uniformly emitted within a (spherical or rectangular) cloud.
     In other words, the medium has a uniformly emissivity.

external_powerlaw
   - A spherical cloud is illuminated by external radiation.
     The radiation field is assumed to be isotropic.
     The density profile is given as a powerlaw: rho(r) = rho0 * r^(par%density_powerlaw_index)

external_rexp
   - A spherical cloud is illuminated by external radiation.
     The radiation field is assumed to be isotropic.
     The density profile is given as an exponential function: rho(r) = rho0 * exp^(-r/par%density_rscale)

external_Plummer
   - A spherical cloud is illuminated by external radiation.
     The density profile is given as a Plummer function: rho(r) = rho0 /(1 +  (-r/par%density_rscale)**2)**(par%density_powerlaw_index/2)
     See Zucker et al. (2021, ApJ, 919, 35).
